
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `monitor-sensor` baraye khandan va namayesh etela'at az sensor-haye monitor estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad darbareye hararat (temperature), voltage, va fan speed (sor'at parch) etela'at kasb konid.  

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `monitor-sensor` --> 🌡️ Namayesh hameye sensor-ha va meghdar-haye anha.
    🔹 `monitor-sensor --help` --> ❓ Namayesh rahnamaye dastoor ba gozine-haye bishtar.
    🔹 `monitor-sensor <name>` --> 🎯 Faghat namayesh etela'at yek sensor khas (be esm).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ monitor-sensor

    🔹 Namayesh etela'at hameye sensor-ha

    $ monitor-sensor temp1

    🔹 Namayesh faghat etela'at sensor ba esme `temp1`

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ monitor-sensor

    CPU Temperature:
        temp1:          +45.0°C  (high = +70.0°C, crit = +90.0°C)

    🔹 Namayesh temperature CPU ba hadaksar meghdar ha.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `monitor-sensor` command is used to read and display information from monitor sensors. This command helps you obtain data about temperature, voltage, and fan speeds.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `monitor-sensor` --> 🌡️ Display all sensors and their values.
    🔹 `monitor-sensor --help` --> ❓ Display command help with more options.
    🔹 `monitor-sensor <name>` --> 🎯 Only display information for a specific sensor (by name).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ monitor-sensor

    🔹 Display information for all sensors.

    $ monitor-sensor temp1

    🔹 Only display information for the sensor named `temp1`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ monitor-sensor

    CPU Temperature:
        temp1:          +45.0°C  (high = +70.0°C, crit = +90.0°C)

    🔹 Displays the CPU temperature along with maximum threshold values.
